                <td class="style2">
                    Method:</td>
                <td>
                    Spectrophotometry (measures total CO2); derived parameter in blood gas analysis.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="style2">
                    Reference Interval:</td>
                <td>
                    22-32 mmol/L. </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="style2">
                    Application :</td>
                <td>
                    Application Acid-base disorders; particularly as initial investigation of 
                    metabolic abnormalities and in defining renal tubular acidosis.
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td class="style5">
                    Interpretation:</td>
                <td class="style6">
                    Serum bicarbonate is increased in metabolic alkalosis and in compensated 
                    respiratory acidosis. Levels are decreased in metabolic acidosis.
                    <br />
                    An artefactual decrease occurs if the collection tube is only partly filled, or 
                    left uncapped, due to loss of CO2.
                    <br />
                    The terms &#39;bicarbonate&#39; and &#39;total carbon dioxide&#39; are often used 
                    interchangeably.                     <br />
                    Although &#39;bicarbonate&#39; is 1-2 mmol/L lower than total carbon dioxide this 
                    difference is not clinically significant.                 </td>
            </tr>
